# Architecture

## Monorepo Layout

```
viberanium/                  # Game engine (Viberanium)
└── src/
    ├── engine/              # Core loop, registry, scene, entity primitives
    ├── math/                # vec3, quat, mat4 — no deps, no classes
    ├── input/               # createInput — keyboard, mouse, pointer lock
    ├── collision/           # Pure character collision math — capsule resolve, broadphase, slope classification (no GL, no registry)
    ├── components/          # Data-only component types + factories
    ├── systems/             # install*System processors (movement, physics, animation, …)
    ├── navigation/          # A* pathfinding helpers
    ├── assets/gltf/         # GLB/glTF loader, cache, runtime scene, materials builder
    ├── definitions/         # Portable Actor/Prop/Skeletal/Level defs + pure helpers (no app coupling)
    ├── spawn/               # Engine spawn helpers (instantiateProp) — no gameplay extras
    ├── render/              # WebGPU device, passes, compute, pipeline installer
    └── index.ts             # Public barrel export (package entry only)
sandbox/                     # Game content
└── src/
    ├── catalog/             # declarative registries: assets, animations, characters, levels, keys
    ├── entities/            # actor, player, enemies, ground — factories, components, systems
    ├── scenes/common/       # createPlayableScene, useLevelScene, prop re-export
    ├── storage/             # levelLocalStore (shared key with construct)
    ├── globals/             # bootstrap, sceneManager
    ├── menus/               # React overlay menus (performance, levels, …)
    ├── ui/                  # SandboxApp shell + theme CSS
    └── SandboxApp.tsx       # package entry re-export
construct/                   # Standalone editor (prop / actor / level tools)
└── src/
    ├── catalog/             # PropDocument, ActorDocument, LevelDocument, manifest
    ├── entities/            # propEditor, actorEditor, levelEditor, gizmos, orbit
    ├── session/             # preview, propEditor, actorEditor, levelEditor slices
    ├── storage/             # prop/actor/level localStore wrappers
    ├── ui/                  # ConstructApp shell + explorer/inspector/modals
    └── …
```

Games import the engine via `import { ... } from 'viberanium'`. Gameplay, Kaykit packs, and editor documents never live under `viberanium/definitions/`. Construct never imports sandbox; sandbox never imports construct. Levels are a scene specialization: every level loads as a scene; not every scene is a level.

### `viberanium/definitions` contract

Portable definition shapes and pure data helpers only. Must be understandable with zero knowledge of sandbox or construct. No Kaykit defaults, no `aiPackage`, no spawn/load, no registries, no document parse/serialize.

Includes portable `LevelDefinition` (indexed simple/standard props and actors + composition TRS + `navGrid`). Authoring fields (`version`, groups, instance names, `aiPackage`) live on Construct `LevelDocument` / `.level` files only.

### `viberanium/spawn` contract

Shared spawn helpers such as `instantiateProp(PropDefinition → entities)`. No Construct editor tags, no sandbox gameplay components (`testAi`, player).

## Game vs Scene Registry

- **Game registry** (`game.registry`) — persistent entities, render pipeline, global input handlers, scene manager
- **Scene registry** (`scene.registry`) — ephemeral; created per level visit, destroyed on exit
- `game.setActiveScene(scene)` unloads the previous scene synchronously before activating the next

Session-scoped caches (`GltfCache`, `TextureCache`) live in bootstrap and survive level transitions. Scene registries, entities, nav grids, and GPU meshes for level content do not.

## Naming Conventions

| Pattern | Example | Use for |
|---------|---------|---------|
| `createX()` | `createTransform()`, `createGltfCache()` | Data factory — returns a plain object |
| `installXSystem()` | `installMovementSystem()` | System installer — registers actions on registry |
| `useX()` | `useRegistry()`, `useLevelScene()` | Engine/game primitive — creates and owns internal state |
| `buildX()` | `buildGltfMaterials()`, `updateNavGridBlocked()` | Pure transform/builder — no side effects |
| `loadX()` | `loadSkeletalCharacter()` | Async asset resolve — no registry writes |
| `spawnX()` | `spawnSkeletalCharacter()` | Attach loaded data to entities on a registry |

## Code Style

- Arrow functions everywhere; `function` keyword only in module-level helpers inside `.ts` files
- No `class` in game logic; `class` is acceptable only in render passes where constructor injection is cleaner
- Factory functions return plain typed objects — never extend or subclass them
- Every public-facing factory/installer exports its return type explicitly
- Guard throws at entry: `if (!canvas) throw new Error('Missing #game canvas')`
- **Never** add barrel `index.ts` files inside engine or game source trees — the single exception is `viberanium/src/index.ts` (package public API)

## Adding New Features

Follow the manaburn-barcrawl pattern — add a feature folder under `entities/enemies/`:
```
sandbox/src/entities/enemies/spider/
  createSpider.ts
  components/
    spiderAI.ts
  systems/
    spiderSystem.ts
```
Register spawn logic in `catalog/levels/` and `useLevelScene`. Add `GAME_COMPONENT_KEYS.spiderAi` in `catalog/keys/components.ts`. Install feature systems in `createPlayableScene` once per scene instance.

When adding geometry that blocks pathfinding, register a static `collider` and call `markNavGridDirty(scene.registry)`.

## Character collision

CPU cylinder move-and-slide is the canonical gameplay path (`installCharacterPhysicsSystem`). Pure math in `viberanium/collision/`:

| Module | Role |
|--------|------|
| `characterContact.ts` | Capsule-vs-box/cylinder/sphere/ellipsoid narrowphase |
| `characterCollision.ts` | `resolveCylinderMoveAndSlide`, slope classification, wall/slope slide; no floor snap/ground while ascending |
| `collisionBroadphase.ts` | Spatial grid for static obstacle queries |
| `characterCollisionBody.ts` | Resolves a character's `characterCollision`-flagged collider children into a solver `CharacterBodyCylinder` |

**Ramps** have no dedicated type — they are rotated box colliders on props or level placements. Walkable slopes (≤ `floorMaxAngle`, default 50°) set `onGround`; steeper slopes (50°–80°) trigger `character.sliding` with automatic downhill movement; near-vertical faces act as walls.

Body dimensions come from the character's `collider` children spawned by `spawn/spawnActorColliders.ts` (bone-attached, character-local, or attachment-local — never a collider on the character root itself), flagged `characterCollision: true` when their `ActorColliderDef.collision === true`. Bone-attached **physics bodies** follow **bind-pose** bones (cached model-space offset × character root via `installHitboxFollowSystem`) — they do **not** crouch with landing/run clips. Combat hitboxes/hurtboxes (`characterCollision` unset) still sample animated poses. Nested (non-bone) collider children follow their parent transform. An actor with zero `collision: true` colliders has no resolvable body — `characterPhysicsSystem` skips it entirely (no movement, no physics). While ascending (`vy > 0`), `resolveCylinderMoveAndSlide` skips ground-plane snap and floor grounding so jumps work when embedded or flush with a surface. `character` holds physics state only (`velocity`, `onGround`, `sliding`, `groundNormal`, …). Optional GPU collision (`installCollisionSystem` + `collisionPass`) is exported but not used in sandbox scenes.

## Skeletal characters

Declarative defs in `catalog/characters/` → `loadSkeletalCharacter` (data only) → `spawnSkeletalCharacter` (registry writes) via `entities/actor/`.

Root entity holds `skeletalModel`, `meshDraws`, `animationClipMap`, `animationStateMachine`, and `children`. Attachments (helmet, jetpack, blade) are **child entities** with `childOf` + `boneAttachment` + `meshDraws` — never orphan body render sub-entities or shared `Transform` refs.

